## Relevance of Data-driven approach in Real Estate


## About the Data: Source & Characteristics

-   The original dataset was a csv file containing real estate listings in the USA categorised by states, city and zipcode.
-   Includes 12 different features and more than 2 million entries 
-   he data had 6 categorical variables some of which had highly cardinality.

## Data Cleaning: Before Sampling 

 - Dropped the states that weren't in mainland USA.
 - Created a unique id using composite key to remove duplicates. 
 - Only included the most recent sale of observations.
 - Included a column called sale frequency that represents the number of times the house has been sold in the past.

## Sampling Technique
- Stratified sampling based on house size, number of bedrooms and baths

```{r Histogram displaying house size distribution}

ggplot(clean_data, aes(x = house_size)) +
  geom_histogram(binwidth = 100, fill = "blue", color = "white", alpha = 0.7) +
  labs(
    title = "House Size Distribution",
    x = "House Size (sq ft)",
    y = "Count"
  ) +
  theme_bw()
```
## Data Preprocessing: After Sampling 

## Data Exploration 
 - Analysed ratios to gain insights from the data
         - Price per square foot 
         - Bathrooms/Bedrooms

```{r Plot showing Bathroom to Bedroom Ratio}
ratiob <- stratified_sample%>%
  mutate(ratio_bb = bath/bed)

#Summary statistics of this new variable
summary(ratiob$ratio_bb) #There are maximum three bathrooms per bedroom which is acceptable

# Visual Inspection
ratiob %>% 
  dplyr::select(ratio_bb) %>% 
  gather() %>% 
  ggplot(aes(value)) +
  facet_wrap(~ key, scales = "free") +
  geom_bar()  
```

